</ol><p><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"></p><p>Concept 1 : <strong>Air pressure</strong></p><p>Air pressure plays a huge role, along with the skirt. As the leaf blower continues to blow, air pressure inside the skirt builds. When under pressure, the air molecules try to spread out. However, the skirt prevents that from happening so that the air is forced to escape from the hole made at the bottom side of the skirt. If the air pressure inside the skirt rises to the point where the air molecules exert more force than the weight of the hovercraft, the hovercraft is lifted.</p><p>Concept 2 : <strong>Fr</strong><strong>iction</strong></p><p> Friction is the resistance to sliding motion between two surfaces that come into contact with each other. In our case with the hovercraft, there needs to be as little friction as possible between the skirt and the ground to avoid potential damage and to glide faster.</p><p>Concept 3 : <strong>T</strong><strong>orque</strong></p><p> Torque is the amount of force acting on an object that causes the object to rotate. The object then rotates about its axis. So in our case, the rudders direct the air flow in an appropriate direction so as to provide the necessary torque ( Newtons Third Law )</p><p>We have referred to the following tutorial to strengthen our concepts - </p><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zPIN1iOoadw">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zPIN1iOoadw</a></p>
